flowRoot.flowPara: The becquerel is a unit that describes the activity of a radioactive source.
(The CIPM* would like it to be the only unit you use to describe the activity of a source.)
Discovered radioactivity by combining a small jar of uranium with photographic paper.
* CIPM is the International Committee for Weights and Measures. They help define standard international (SI) units.
The curie is another unit that describes the activity of a radioactive source.
One curie is defined to be the activity of one gram of radium.
Discovered radioactive elements radium (Ra) and polonium (Po).
The gray is a unit that describes the absorbed dose.
Radiation that deposits energy densely in tissue is more damaging.
Built a neutron generator and studied how radiation affects different types of cells.
The rad, or "radiation absorbed dose", is another unit that describes an absorbed dose.
The sievert is a unit that measures the biological effect of an absorbed dose.
The absorbed dose, adjusted for biology, is called the "dose equivalent"
Note that the units for the dose equivalent are the same as for the absorbed dose.
Developed instruments to accurately measure absorbed doses.
The rem, or "Roentgen equivalent man", is another unit describing the biologically-adjusted absorbed dose.
Discovered x-rays. Also one of the few early radioactivity researchers who used protective lead shielding.
